# pyenv
#   For a library or package, you might want to ignore these files since the Python version
#   is usually managed by the user. However, for a project/app, it might be useful to share
#   them.
# .python-version

# pipenv
#   According to pypa/pipenv#598, it is recommended to include Pipfile.lock in version control.
#   However, in case of collaboration, if you want to avoid potential conflicts or if you
#   prefer to let the user generate their own lock file, you can uncomment the following line.
#Pipfile.lock

# poetry
#   Similar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include poetry.lock in version control.
#   https://python-poetry.org/docs/basic-usage/#commit-your-poetrylock-file-to-version-control
#poetry.lock

# pdm
#   Similar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include pdm.lock in version control.
#pdm.lock
#   pdm stores project-wide configurations in .pdm-python
.pdm-python
#   pdm stores cached wheels in __pypackages__
